**IsSidonSet S:** All pairwise sums are distinct.

a + b = c + d implies {a,b} = {c,d}

Also called B₂ sequences. Named after Simon Sidon who studied them in 1932.

**A₁(N):** Number of maximal Sidon subsets of {1,...,N}

**A(N):** Number of all Sidon subsets of {1,...,N}

The key relationship: A(N) ≤ A₁(N) · (subsets per maximal)

**erdos_862_main:**

A₁(N) ≥ 2^{(0.16+o(1))√N}

**Derivation:**
- A(N) ≥ 2^{1.16√N} (Saxton-Thomason)
- Each maximal has ≤ 2^{1·√N} Sidon subsets
- A₁(N) ≥ A(N) / 2^{√N} ≥ 2^{(1.16-1)√N} = 2^{0.16√N}

**erdos_862_summary:**

1. Question 2: YES, A₁(N) > 2^{N^c}
2. Question 1: NO, A₁(N) is NOT < 2^{o(√N)}
3. Precise bound: A₁(N) ≥ 2^{(0.16+o(1))√N}

**Status:** SOLVED by Saxton-Thomason (2015)

A landmark application of the hypergraph container method.
